<L>Lur'd by the beating of his pul&s;e, to li&s;t</L>
<L>With ev'ry lu&s;t, that wars again&s;t his peace;</L>
<L>And &s;ets him quite at variance with him&s;elf.</L>
<L>Thy&s;elf, fir&s;t, know; then love: a &s;elf there is</L>
<L>Of virtue fond, that kindles at her charms.</L>
<L>A &s;elf there is, as fond of ev'ry vice,</L>
<L>While ev'ry virtue wounds it to the heart:</L>
<L>Humility degrades it, ju&s;tice robs,</L>
<L>Ble&s;t bounty beggars it, fair truth betrays,</L>
<L>And godlike magnanimity de&s;troys.</L>
<L>This &s;elf, when rival to the former, &s;corn;</L>
<L>When not in competition, kindly treat,</L>
<L>Defend it, feed it:&mdash;But when virtue bids,</L>
<L>To&s;s it, or to the fowls, or to the flames.</L>
